problem link: https://leetcode.com/problems/palindrome-linked-list/description/

Intuition
A palindrome reads the same forwards and backwards. In an array we can compare elements from both ends, but in a singly linked list we cannot move backward. To overcome this, we find the middle of the list using slow and fast pointers, reverse the second half of the list, and then compare nodes from the beginning of the list and the beginning of the reversed second half. If all corresponding values match, the linked list is a palindrome; otherwise, it is not.

Approach
Use slow and fast pointers to find the middle of the linked list.
Reverse the second half of the linked list in-place.
Initialize two pointers: one at the head of the list and one at the head of the reversed second half.
Compare the values of both pointers while traversing the reversed half. If any values differ, return False.
If all corresponding values match, return True.
Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n)
Space complexity:
O(1)
Code
# Definition for singly-linked list.
# class ListNode:
#     def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):
#         self.val = val
#         self.next = next
class Solution:
    def isPalindrome(self, head: Optional[ListNode]) -> bool:
        slow = head
        fast = head 
        while fast and fast.next:
            slow = slow.next
            fast = fast.next.next

        prev = None
        curr = slow
        while curr != None:
            newnode = curr.next
            curr.next = prev
            prev = curr
            curr = newnode
        ptr1 = head
        ptr2 = prev
        while ptr2:
            if ptr1.val != ptr2.val:
                return False
            ptr1 = ptr1.next
            ptr2 = ptr2.next

        return True
